* Contents:
============

* What does the program do?
===========================

The program creates a child process using fork().

The child process acts as the consumer, while the parent process acts as the producer.

The producer opens an input file and reads its contents in chunks.
These chunks are then written into an unnamed pipe buffer until all data
has been processed.

The consumer reads data from the pipe buffer in smaller batches and writes
it to an output file.

During execution, both processes print messages to the console to show
their current actions. This allows verification of correct behavior and
helps observe the synchronization between producer and consumer.

The execution speed of both processes depends on the sleep() delays.
If one process is significantly faster, it will dominate execution and
produce more actions than the other. Therefore, similar sleep durations
are required to achieve balanced, alternating execution.

---

* How to run the program:
=========================

To compile:
make

To run:
make run

To clean build files:
make clean

To check file equality:
make check
